---
import ServicePage from '@layouts/ServicePage.astro';
import type { Faq } from '@data/site';

const faqs: Faq[] = [
  {
    question: 'Where do septic tanks usually sit on a property?',
    answer:
      'Commonly between the house and the drain field, often 10–25 feet from the foundation on the side where the main sewer line exits. That is a starting point, not a rule — older rural properties in particular can surprise you.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Are there records of where my tank is?',
    answer:
      'Sometimes. Depending on when the system was installed, county or state records may include a system sketch. Previous owners, neighbors who used the same installer, and old service receipts are also useful sources.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How do providers find a tank with no records?',
    answer:
      'Typical methods include following the sewer line from the house, probing likely areas, and electronic locating — flushing a small transmitter that is tracked from the surface. Availability and methods vary by provider.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I look for it myself first?',
    answer:
      'Careful observation is fine: look for lid-sized depressions or mounds, areas where snow melts first, or the cleanout direction leaving the house. Do not excavate blindly near utilities, and never open a tank lid you find — septic gases and open tanks are dangerous.',
  },
];
---

<ServicePage
  title="Septic Tank Locating in Cookeville, TN"
  description="Request septic tank locating in Cookeville, TN when the tank location is unknown. Records, locating methods and how to prepare the property for pumping or inspection."
  h1="Septic Tank Locating in Cookeville, TN"
  breadcrumbLabel="Septic Tank Locating — Cookeville"
  serviceName="Septic Tank Locating"
  areaServed="Cookeville and Putnam County, Tennessee"
  intro="Bought a place with no septic records? Tank locating finds the lids and access points so pumping, inspection or repair can actually happen."
  faqs={faqs}
  formHeading="Request Tank Locating"
  related={[
    { label: 'Septic Pumping in Cookeville', href: '/septic-pumping-cookeville-tn/', blurb: 'usually the reason the tank needed finding' },
    { label: 'Septic Inspections in Cookeville', href: '/septic-inspection-cookeville-tn/', blurb: 'worth pairing once access is established' },
    { label: 'Septic Maintenance Guide', href: '/septic-maintenance/', blurb: 'keep records so this only has to happen once' },
  ]}
>
  <h2>Why Tank Location Becomes a Mystery</h2>
  <p>
    Lids get buried under decades of topsoil and landscaping. Properties change hands and the
    paperwork doesn’t follow. Additions and decks get built over what used to be open lawn. It is
    genuinely common for a new owner in the Cookeville area — especially on older rural property —
    to have no idea where the tank sits. Nothing is wrong with the system; it has just gone quiet.
  </p>

  <h2>Start With Records and Memory</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>County or state septic records, where they exist for the installation era</li>
    <li>Previous owners, long-time neighbors, or the builder</li>
    <li>Old service receipts, closing documents or home-inspection reports</li>
    <li>The direction the main sewer line leaves the house (visible at the cleanout or in a crawlspace)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How Providers Locate Tanks</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Line tracing</strong> — following the sewer line from the house toward the tank</li>
    <li><strong>Probing</strong> — systematically checking likely areas with a soil probe</li>
    <li><strong>Electronic locating</strong> — a small flushable transmitter tracked from the surface</li>
    <li><strong>Surface reading</strong> — depressions, mounds, and grass that behaves differently over lids</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Availability and methods vary; some pumping providers include locating, others treat it as separate work.</p>

  <h2>Preparing the Property</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Clear access to the area between the house and the suspected tank zone</li>
    <li>Know where your water line and well (if any) run, to the extent possible</li>
    <li>Share anything you have — photos, sketches, memories of past service visits</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Once the tank is found, record the location properly — measurements from two fixed corners of
    the house beat memory every time. The
    <a href="/septic-maintenance/">septic maintenance guide</a> covers what else is worth keeping
    on file.
  </p>
</ServicePage>
